|Castleford]])\n|38\n|- style=\"background:#f5faff;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | [[Super League XXIII|2018]]\n|{{leagueicon|Wigan|16}} '''[[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]]''' (22)\n|{{leagueicon|Warrington|16}} [[Warrington Wolves|Warrington]]\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ben Barba]] ({{leagueicon|St. Helens|16}} [[St Helens RFC|St Helens]])\n|28\n|- style=\"background:#f5faff;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | [[Super League XXIV|2019]]\n| {{leagueicon|St Helens|16}} '''[[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]]''' (14)\n| {{leagueicon|Salford City|16}} [[Salford Red Devils|Salford]]\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Tommy Makinson]] ({{leagueicon|St. Helens|16}} [[St Helens RFC|St Helens]])\n|23\n|}\n\n==Winning records by club==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!\n! style=\"width:25%;\"| Club\n! Winners\n! style=\"width:8%;\"|Runners-up\n! Winning seasons\n|-\n|1||{{leagueicon|Wigan|16}} [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]]||22||16||1908/09, 1921/22, 1925/26, 1933/34, 1945/46, 1946/47, 1949/50, 1951/52, 1959/60, 1986/87, 1989/90, 1990/91, 1991/92, 1992/93, 1993/94, 1994/95, 1995/96, 1998, 2010, 2013, 2016, 2018\n|-\n|2||align=left|{{leagueicon|St Helens|16}} [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]]||14||16|| 1931/32, 1952/53, 1958/59, 1965/66, 1969/70, 1970/71, 1974/75, 1996, 1999, 2000, 2002, 2006, 2014, 2019\n|-\n|3||align=left|{{leagueicon|Leeds|16}} [[Leeds Rhinos|Leeds]]||11||11||1960/61, 1968/69, 1971/72, 2004, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2015, 2017\n|-\n|4||align=left|{{leagueicon|Huddersfield|16}} [[Huddersfield Giants|Huddersfield]]||7||6||1911/12, 1912/13, 1914/15, 1928/29, 1929/30, 1948/49, 1961/62\n|-\n|5||align=left|{{leagueicon|Bradford|16}} [[Bradford Bulls|Bradford]] ||6||7||1979/80, 1980/81, 1997, 2001, 2003, 2005\n|-\n|6||align=left|{{leagueicon|Salford City Reds|16}} [[Salford Red Devils|Salford]]<ref name=\"salford\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reds.co.uk/history|title=Salford Red Devils: Official Club Website|publisher=Salford Red Devils|accessdate=13 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107185227/http://www.reds.co.uk/history|archivedate=7 November 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>||6||4||1913/14, 1932/33, 1936/37, 1938/39, 1973/74, 1975/76\n|-\n|7||align=left|{{leagueicon|Hull|16}} [[Hull F.C.]]||6||4||1919/20, 1920/21, 1935/36, 1955/56, 1957/58, 1982/83\n|-\n|8||align=left|{{leagueicon|Swinton|16}} [[Swinton Lions|Swinton]]||6||2||1926/27, 1927/28, 1930/31, 1934/35, 1962/63, 1963/64\n|-\n|9||align=left|{{leagueicon|Hull KR|16}} [[Hull Kingston Rovers|Hull KR]]||5||3||1922/23, 1924/25, 1978/79, 1983/84, 1984/85\n|-\n|10||align=left|{{leagueicon|Oldham|16}} [[Oldham R.L.F.C.|Oldham]]||4||5||1904/05, 1909/10, 1910/11, 1956/57\n|-\n|11||align=left|{{leagueicon|Halifax|16}} [[Halifax R.L.F.C.|Halifax]]||4||5||1902/03, 1906/07, 1964/65, 1985/86\n|-\n|12||align=left|{{leagueicon|Warrington|16}} [[Warrington Wolves|Warrington]]||3||11||1947/48, 1953/54, 1954/55\n|-\n|13||align=left|{{leagueicon|Widnes|16}} [[Widnes Vikings|Widnes]]||3||4||1977/78, 1987/88, 1988/89\n|-\n|14||align=left|{{leagueicon|Hunslet|16}} ''[[Hunslet F.C. (1883)|Hunslet]]'' \u00a7||2||2||1907/08, 1937/38\n|-\n|15||align=left|{{leagueicon|Wakefield|16}} [[Wakefield Trinity|Wakefield]]||2||2||1966/67, 1967/68\n|-\n|16||align=left|{{leagueicon|Leigh|16}} [[Leigh Centurions|Leigh]]||2||0||1905/06, 1981/82\n|-\n|17||align=left|{{leagueicon|Featherstone|16}} [[Featherstone Rovers|Featherstone]]||1||2||1976/77\n|-\n|18||align=left|''[[Bradford Park Avenue A.F.C.#Rugby football|Bradford F.C.]]'' \u00a7||1||1||1903/04\n|-\n|19||align=left|{{leagueicon|Workington|16}} [[Workington Town|Workington]]||1||1||1950/51\n|-\n|20||align=left|{{leagueicon|Dewsbury|16}} [[Dewsbury Rams|Dewsbury]]||1||1||1972/73\n|-\n|21||align=left|{{leagueicon|Brisbane|16}} ''[[Manningham F.C.|Manningham]]'' \u00a7||1||0||1895/96\n|-\n|22||align=left|{{leagueicon|Cronulla|16}} ''[[Broughton Rangers|Broughton]]'' \u00a7||1||0||1901/02\n|-\n|23||align=left|{{leagueicon|Batley|16}} [[Batley Bulldogs|Batley]]||1||0||1923/24\n|-\n|24||align=left|{{leagueicon|Castleford|16}} [[Castleford Tigers|Castleford]]||0||3||\n|-\n|25||align=left|{{leagueicon|Port Moresby Vipers|16}} ''[[St Helens Recs]]'' \u00a7||0||1||\n|-\n|26||align=left|{{leagueicon|London Broncos|16}} [[London Broncos|London]]||0||1||\n|}\n* ''\u00a7 Denotes club now [[List of defunct rugby league clubs|defunct]]''\n\n==See also==\n* [[Super League]]\n* [[Rugby Football League Championship First Division]]\n* [[Challenge Cup]]\n* [[Rugby league county leagues]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\nThe '''British men's rugby league champions''' are the winners of the highest league in British rugby league, which since [[Super League I|1996]] is the [[Super League]]. Although the league is based in Britain, teams from Europe and North Anerica can win the league due to teams from France and Canada competing in the [[British rugby league system]].\n\nFollowing the schism in 1895 that saw 22 Northern rugby clubs split from the [[Rugby Football Union]] and form the [[Rugby Football League|Northern Union]], the 22 clubs were organised into [[Rugby Football League Championship First Division|one league]]. At the end of the [[1895\u201396 Northern Rugby Football Union season|1895\u201396 season]], [[Manningham FC|Manningham]] were the first club to be crowned champions, finishing one point ahead of [[Halifax RFC|Halifax]].<ref>{{cite news\n | last =Baker\n | first =Andrew\n | title =100 years of rugby league: From the great divide to the Super era\n | newspaper = [[The Independent]]\n | date =1995-08-20\n | url =https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/100-years-of-rugby-league-from-the-great-divide-to-the-super-era-1597130.html\n | accessdate =2009-09-25 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the success of the [[Rugby Football League|Northern Unions]] first season, more clubs defected from the [[Rugby Football Union]] to join the new league. After concerns around travel and costs were expressed, the decision was made that the competition should be split into two separate county championships: Lancashire and Yorkshire Leagues. County leagues were in place for the next five seasons until 1901\u201302 were the top seven sides from each league resigned to merge to form a new league. The only other times that there was no [[Rugby Football League Championship First Division|major championship]] was when there were outbrakes of war.\n\nDuring the late 1980s and early 90s, [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]] became the only full time professional club and dominated in every competition. A new Super League began to be mooted during the [[Super League war]] in Australia as a way for [[Rupert Murdoch]] to gain a upper hand in broadcasting supremacy with the [[Australian Rugby League]]. British clubs were approached to form a Super League with a cash insentive. Part of the deal was switching the sport to summer and the merger of some clubs, the latter not taking place due to huge protest from fans. All four Super League champions; [[St Helens RFC|St Helens]], [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]], [[Bradford Bulls|Bradford]] and [[Leeds Rhinos|Leeds]] have all previously won the old [[Rugby Football League Championship First Devision|First Division]].\n\nOnly three clubs to have been crowned champions are not in existence today. During the reclassification of the Championship in 1901, the league was split into two divisions. [[Manningham FC|Manningham]] were placed in the [[Rugby Football League Championship Second Division|Second Division]], finishing 10th out of 18 teams. At the end of the season a series of meetings was held about establishing a [[Football League]] club in the city. During a annual meeting the committee voted to switch to association football, becoming [[Bradford City]]. A similar situation occurred at [[Bradford FC]] in 1907 when a narrow majority of members voted to withdraw from the Northern Union in favour of association football, forming [[Bradford Park Avenue]]. [[Broughton Rangers]] struggled post war and folded in 1955 after a failed name change to Belle Vue Rangers in 1946.\n\n[[Hunslet FC]] were the fourth former champions to fold after financial issues[http://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/local-news/rugby-league-star-was-most-expensive-player-1-6493832], player strikes and a stadium fire that led to the club selling the land to developers before being eventually wound up. Unlike the other three clubs who no longer exist, a pheonix club, [[Hunslet RLFC|New Hunslet]] were formed in 1973 and still exist now.<ref name=hawkhist>{{cite web|url=http://www.hunslethawks.co.uk/info/history |title=History |publisher=Hunslet RFLC |accessdate=27 November 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==List==\n===RFL Championship First Division (1895\u20131996)===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:9%\"|Year\n! style=\"width:18%\"|Champions<br />(number of titles)\n! style=\"width:18%\"|Runners-up\n! style=\"width:27%\"|Leading tryscorer<br>(club)\n! style=\"width:1%\"|Trys\n|- style=\"background:#f5faff;\"\n| [[1895\u201396 Northern Rugby Football Union season|1895\u201396]]\n| {{leagueicon|Brisbane|16}} '''[[Manningham F.C.|Manningham]]'''\n|  {{leagueicon|Halifax|16}} [[Halifax R.L.F.C.|Halifax]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Jack Hurst]] ({{leagueicon|oldham|16}} [[Oldham RLFC|Oldham]])\n|28\n|- style=\"background:#f5faff;\"\n| colspan=5 style=\"text-align: center;\" | [[1896\u201397 Northern Rugby Football Union season|1896]]\u2013[[1900\u201301 Northern Rugby Football Union season|1901]] [[Rugby league county leagues|County Leagues]]\n|- style=\"background:#f5faff;\"\n| [[1901\u201302 Northern Rugby Football Union season|1901\u201302]]\n|  {{leagueicon|Cronulla|16}} '''[[Broughton Rangers|Broughton]]'''\n|  {{leagueicon|salford city|16}} [[Salford Red Devils|Salford]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Robert Wilson (rugby league)|Rob Wilson]] ({{leagueicon|Cronulla|16}} [[Broughton Rangers|Broughton]])\n|38\n|- style=\"background:#f5faff;